{{Infobox person | name = Edith Irby Jones | image = [[File:EdithIrbyJones.jpg|EdithIrbyJones]] | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = Edith Mae Irby | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1927|12|23}} | birth_place = near [[Conway, Arkansas]] | nationality = American | occupation = physician | years_active = 1952–present | known_for = first African-American student to attend a racially mixed class in the Southern United States }} '''Edith Irby Jones''' (born December 23, 1927) is an American physician who was the first [[African American]] to be accepted as a non-segregated student at the [[University of Arkansas]] Medical School and the first black student to attend racially mixed classes in the [[Southern United States|American South]]. She was the first African American to graduate from a southern medical school, first black intern in the state of Arkansas, and later first black intern at [[Baylor College of Medicine]]. Jones was the first woman president of the [[National Medical Association]]. She has been honored by many awards, including induction into both the University of Arkansas College of Medicine Hall of Fame and the inaugural group of women inducted into the [[Arkansas Women's Hall of Fame]].
==Biography== Edith Mae Irby was born on December 23, 1927, near [[Conway, Arkansas|Conway]] in [[Faulkner County, Arkansas]], to Mattie (née Buice) and Robert Irby. At the age of eight, she lost her father, an older sister died at 12 years of age from [[typhoid fever]], and Irby herself suffered from [[rheumatic fever]] as a child. These were motivating factors in her desire to help those who were underserved and impoverished and which propelled her toward a career in medicine. Her mother relocated the family to [[Hot Springs, Arkansas|Hot Springs]], where Irby graduated from Langston Secondary School in 1944. After winning a scholarship, she studied chemistry, biology and physics at [[Knoxville College]] in [[Knoxville, Tennessee]].<ref name="Hall of Fame">{{cite web|title=Dr. Edith Irby Jones|url=http://www.arwomenshalloffame.com/#/edith-jones/|publisher=Arkansas Women's Hall of Fame|accessdate=December 26, 2015|location=Little Rock, Arkansas|date=August 27, 2015}}</ref> Irby was well aware of the role she was playing and obligation she had for the black community. One of her teachers had helped her attain the scholarship, members of the local African American community collected change and the black press ran a campaign in the ''[[Daisy Bates (civil rights activist)#Arkansas State Press|Arkansas State-Press]]'' which they donated to help with her tuition and living expenses.<ref name="National Library of Medicine bio">{{cite web|title=Dr. Edith Irby Jones|url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/changingthefaceofmedicine/physicians/biography_175.html|publisher=National Library of Medicine|accessdate=December 26, 2015|location=Bethesda, Maryland}}</ref> During her schooling, she secretly made trips with teams of workers from the [[NAACP]] to enroll members for the organization.{{sfn|More|1999|p=237}} She graduated with her BS from Knoxville College in 1948 and then completed a graduate course at [[Northwestern University]] in [[Evanston, Illinois]] to prepare for Medical School.<ref name="graduation 1952">{{cite news|title=University to Graduate First Negro Student|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3893535/university_to_graduate_first_negro/|accessdate= December 26, 2015|work=Hope Star|date=May 19, 1952|location=Hope, Arkansas|page=3|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref>
{{quote box|width=30em|bgcolor=#c6dbf7|align=left|quote="I hope to make a record that will reflect to the honor of my race and that will obviously show that we only want to be accorded the rights deserved by human beings and good American citizens."|source=—''The Pittsburgh Courier'', 9 October 1948<ref name="aware of the responsibility">{{cite news|title=The Courier Salutes|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3893067/the_courier_salutes_the_pittsburgh/|accessdate=December 26, 2015|work=The Pittsburgh Courier|date=9 October 1948|location=Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|page=16|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref>}} That same year, she was admitted to the University of Arkansas Medical School, as part of a racially mixed class, and made headlines across the United States<ref name="National Library of Medicine">{{cite web|title=Edith Irby Jones, M.D.|url=https://www.nlm.nih.gov/locallegends/Biographies/Jones_Edith.html|publisher=National Library of Medicine|accessdate=December 26, 2015|location=Bethesda, Maryland|date=2005}}</ref> from New York<ref name="New York Age">{{cite news|title=University of Ark. Admits Negro Girl to Medical School|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3892746/the_new_york_age/|accessdate=December 26, 2015|work=The New York Age|date=August 28, 1948|location=New York, NY|page=1|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> to Oregon<ref name=Oregon>{{cite news|title=Negro Girl Will Enter South Medical School|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3892778/negro_girl_will_enter_south_medical/|accessdate= December 26, 2015|publisher=The Eugene Guard|date=August 25, 1948|location=Eugene, Oregon|page=8|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> to North Dakota<ref name="Bismark ND">{{cite news|title='Jim Crow' Bopped in Arkansas, Not Oklahoma; Wallace Flays It|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3892808/the_bismarck_tribune/|accessdate=December 26, 2015|work=The Bismark Tribune|date=August 24, 1948|location=Bismark, North Dakota|page=10|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> to Texas.<ref name="Abilene, Texas">{{cite news|title=Negro Girl Enters Medical School|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3892844/negro_girl_enters_medical_school/|accessdate=December 26, 2015|work=Abilene Reporter-News|date=September 21, 1948|location=Abilene, Texas|page=13|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> She became the first African American to be accepted in any school in the Southern United States and the news was carried in September 1948 in ''[[The Crisis]]'',<ref name="60th Anniversary Issue">{{cite journal|editor1-last=Moon|editor1-first=Henry Lee|title=University of Arkansas Is First|journal=The Crisis|date=November 1970|volume=77|issue=9|pages=331–332|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NV2MtmlurRYC&pg=PA331|accessdate= December 26, 2015|publisher=The Crisis Publishing Company, Inc.|location=New York, NY}}</ref> ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' Magazine's January 31, 1949 issue, the January 1949 edition of ''[[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]]'',{{sfn|Smith|1996|p=346}} as well as other national publications such as ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' and ''[[The Washington Post]]''. During her second year of school, Irby and Dr. James B. Jones, a professor married; they subsequently had three children.<ref name="Hall of Fame" /> In 1952, Jones received her [[Doctor of Medicine]] degree, as the first African-American graduate from [[University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences]] and was accepted to complete the first residency by an African American at a hospital in Arkansas.<ref name="graduation 1952" />
==Career== Upon her graduation, Jones returned to Hot Springs and practiced medicine there for six years.<ref name="National Library of Medicine bio" /> When tension over the [[Little Rock Nine]] polarized Arkansas, and newspapers began to spotlight her again,<ref name="central high school">{{cite news|title=Something Good in Arkansas|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3893992/something_good_in_arkansas_the/|accessdate=December 27, 2015|work=The Pittsburgh Courier|date=5 July 1958|location=Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|page=12|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> in 1959, they moved to [[Houston, Texas]], where she was accepted as the first black woman intern at the [[Baylor College of Medicine]] Affiliated Hospitals.<ref name="Hall of Fame" /> The segregated staff at the hospital and limited patient rosters in Texas, caused her to finish her last three months of residency at [[Freedman's Hospital]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] In 1962, she founded her private practice<ref name="National Library of Medicine bio" /> in Houston's "third ward", part of the inner city of Houston, to help those who could not access care elsewhere.<ref name="Hall of Fame" /> That same year, she became the chief of cardiology at St. Elizabeth’s Hospital in Houston. She also became an associate chief of medicine at [[Riverside General Hospital]].{{sfn|Smith|1996|p=347}} In 1963, she accepted a post as a Clinical Assistant Professor at Baylor College of Medicine.<ref name="National Library of Medicine" /> Continuing her education, Jones completed graduate courses at the [[West Virginia University School of Medicine|West Virginia College of Medicine]] in 1965 and the [[Cook County Graduate School of Medicine]] in Chicago in 1966.{{sfn|Smith|1996|p=347}} In 1969, she was honored by the Houston Chapter of ''[[Association for Women in Communications|Theta Sigma Phi]]'' professional women with the Matrix Award for Medicine.<ref name="Theta Sigma Phi">{{cite news|title=Press Ladies Breakfast Scheduled for May 4|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3893639/press_ladies_breakfast_scheduled_for/|accessdate= December 26, 2015|work=The Baytown Sun|date=April 4, 1969|location=Baytown, Texas|page=9|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref>
In 1964, Jones was elected to serve as second vice president of the [[National Medical Association]] (NMA).<ref name="VP NMA">{{cite news|title=NMA Concludes 69th Annual Convention|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/3893722/the_pittsburgh_courier/|accessdate=December 26, 2015|work=The Pittsburgh Courier|date=August 29, 1964|location=Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|page=2|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}} {{open access}}</ref> In 1975, she became the first woman to chair the Council on Scientific Assembly for the NMA and then a decade later, she was elected as the first woman president of the organization.{{sfn|Smith|1996|p=347}} In 1986, ''Edith Irby Jones Day'' was proclaimed by the City of Houston and in 1988 she was named Internist of the Year by the [[American Society of Internal Medicine]].<ref name="National Library of Medicine bio" /> She was one of the founders of Mercy Hospital in Houston and one of the 12 physician owners and developers of the Park Plaza Hospital.<ref name="Hall of Fame" /> Jones also supervises residents at the [[University of Texas Health Science Center]] and is active on the board of Planned Parenthood and the Houston School Board.{{sfn|More|1999|p=238}}
Throughout her career, Jones has received many awards and honors for both her professional and volunteer work, including Honorary Doctorates from [[Missouri Valley College]] (1988), [[Mary Holmes College]] (1989), [[Lindenwood College]] (1991), and [[Knoxville College]] (1992);<ref name="National Library of Medicine" /> Southeast Memorial Hospital renamed its ambulatory center in her honor (1998); recipient of the 2001 Oscar E. Edwards Memorial Award for Volunteerism and Community Service from the [[American College of Physicians]]; inducted into the University of Arkansas College of Medicine Hall of Fame (2004); US Congresswoman [[Sheila Jackson Lee]] nominated Jones as a Local Legend for the [[United States National Library of Medicine|National Library of Medicine]];<ref name="Texas House">{{cite web|title=H.R. No. 800|url=http://www.legis.state.tx.us/tlodocs/83R/billtext/html/HR00800I.htm|publisher=Texas House of Representatives|accessdate=December 27, 2015|location=Austin, Texas|date=October 10, 2015}}</ref> induction into the inaugural class of women honored by the [[Arkansas Women's Hall of Fame]] in 2015;<ref name="Hall of Fame" /> and received a commendation from the [[Texas House of Representatives]] for her service in 2015.<ref name="Texas House" /> Two international hospitals also are named in her honor: Dr. Edith Irby Jones Clinic in Vaudreuil, [[Haiti]], which she helped found in 1991,{{sfn|More|1999|p=238}} and the Dr. Edith Irby Jones Emergency Clinic in [[Veracruz, Mexico]].<ref name="Hall of Fame" />
