'''National Trust Party''' ({{lang-fa|حزب اعتماد ملی|Ḥezb-e Eʿtemād-e Mellī}}, also translated as '''National Confidence Party''')<ref name="GMT">{{cite book|author=Gunes Murat Tezcur|title=Muslim Reformers in Iran and Turkey: The Paradox of Moderation|publisher=The University of Texas Press|year=2010|isbn=978-0-292-72197-5|pages=120, 202–203}}
</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/Iranian-Threat/News/Political-factions-competing-in-Irans-parliamentary-elections|title=Political Factions Competing in Iran's Parliamentary Elections|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=14 March 2008|access-date=1 March 2017}}</ref> is an [[Iran]]ian political party based on reformist and populist message.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kaveh-Cyrus Sanandaji (Middle East Center, St. Antony's College, University of Oxford)|title=What Reformists Can Learn From Past Failures|url=https://www.ndi.org/node/15421|publisher=National Democratic Institute|date=April 24, 2009|quote=''Karroubi continues to expound a populist message''}}</ref>

It was established in 2005 by former [[Majlis of Iran|Parliament]] speaker [[Mehdi Karroubi]] following his defeat in [[Iranian presidential election, 2005|2005 presidential election]].<ref name="Tehran Bureau">{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/tehranbureau/2009/05/the-political-groups.html|title=The Political Groups|publisher=[[Tehran Bureau]]|author=[[Muhammad Sahimi]]|accessdate=21 August 2015|date=12 May 2009}}</ref> National Trust Party cooperates with the Reformists' Supreme Council for Policymaking.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.criticalthreats.org/briefs/iran-2017-presidential-election-tracker|author=Caitlin Shayda Pendleton|title=Iran 2017 Presidential Election Tracker|date=23 September 2016|access-date=5 May 2017|work=AEI’s Critical Threats Project}}</ref>

==Platform==
The party has opposed dictating the [[state religion]] in Iran and called for an amendment for the [[constitution of Iran]] that would limit absolute power of [[Supreme leader of Iran|Supreme leader]], while endorsing [[Guardianship of the Islamic Jurist]].<ref name="GMT"/> In foreign policy, it wants détente with the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite journal|first1=Hossein|last1=Asayesh|first2=Adlina Ab. |last2=Halim|first3=Jayum A.|last3=Jawan|first4=Seyedeh Nosrat|last4=Shojaei|url=http://www.ccsenet.org/journal/index.php/jpl/article/download/9606/6898|title=Political Party in Islamic Republic of Iran: A Review|journal=Journal of Politics and Law|volume=4|number=1|pages=221–230|year=March 2011|issn=1913-9047|publisher=Canadian Center of Science and Education}}</ref> The party regards itself as being committed to the [[political thought and legacy of Ruhollah Khomeini]].<ref>{{cite web|title=National Trust (''E‘temād-e Mellī'')|url=http://irandataportal.syr.edu/wp-content/uploads/national-trust.pdf|work=Iran Data Portal|publisher=Syracuse University|accessdate=10 May 2017|date=15 June 2011}}</ref>

Writing in ''[[Iranian Studies (journal)|Iranian Studies]]'', Kaveh-Cyrus Sanandaji states that the party projects a more moderate-reformist platform than the mainstream reformist current associated with [[Mohammad Khatami]], given that it purportedly “does not question the Islamic character of the regime”.<ref>{{citation|title=The Eighth Majles Elections in the Islamic Republic of Iran: A Division in Conservative Ranks and the Politics of Moderation|author=Kaveh-Cyrus Sanandaji|journal=Iranian Studies|volume=42|number=4|publisher=Routledge|year=2009|pages=621–648|doi=10.1080/00210860903106345}}</ref> According to [[Muhammad Sahimi]], the party and has tried to attract the disaffected reformists who are not happy with the [[Islamic Iran Participation Front|Participation Front]], [[Mojahedin of the Islamic Revolution of Iran Organization|Mojahedin]], or the [[Executives of Construction Party|Executives of Construction]] and "is more like a moderate right-wing party than a true reformist/democratic organization".<ref name="Tehran Bureau"/>

